onires53 (jason.r.serino@gmail.com)
2016-11-04 18:20:53

The ability to have a suedo DEP enablement scenario through their Knox registration methods, as well as leveraging the "container-only mode" that CORE 9.2 will support.

onires53 (jason.r.serino@gmail.com)
2016-11-04 18:22:40

That container only mode will also allow us to use the "native" ECC apps.

MobilXperts Admin (mobilxpertsslack@gmail.com)
2016-11-04 18:24:10

How does the Knox registration look in terms of similarity to DEP?

onires53 (jason.r.serino@gmail.com)
2016-11-04 19:04:16

Very similar. They have a portal that the carrier's use to add your Samsung devices to once purchased. That is tied to you MDM. Once that is done, they are forced to register the device against your MDM and if you have additional Knox licensing setup you can then have it configured with the additional security api's.

MobilXperts Admin (mobilxpertsslack@gmail.com)
2016-11-04 19:12:32

Ah, nice. Does the device launch straight into the registration once it’s reset or regardless of the state the user has it in?

The issue is EAP-LEAP. This does not work with Android. There is a reference to this in an old v7 Admin Guide https://community.mobileiron.com/docs/DOC-1032

Simon Hardy-Bistagne (simon@smnhdy.com)
2018-04-13 19:51:33

Just a headsup to all...

In past versions of Android, the native Samsung appstore wasn't considered as a non-google appstore. In Oreo Google now flags the Samsung store as non-google.

Result is that unless you allow apps to be installed from unknown sources (non-google appstores) the native samsung apps will no longer be able to be updated, or installed. That will include things like Dex, always on display updates etc.

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2018-04-13 19:56:24

This seems both good and bad. But ultimately fixable by Samsung as Sony have a similar private store.

*Thread Reply:* So the nice reatures are the built in antivirus and network security tools along with the age based restrictions you can tag to the kids devices.

The qos isn't amazing but it's there.

Ddns built in, DHCP, port forwarding dn address reservation all there as you'd expect.

The only thing I'm missing is either multiple ssid capabilities or the ability to name the 2.4 and 5ghz networks separately.

Get your apps ready for the 64-bit requirement
64-bit CPUs deliver faster, richer experiences for your users. Adding a 64-bit version of your app provides performance improvements, makes way for future innovation, and sets you up for devices with 64-bit only hardware.

David F (david.fink@gov.bc.ca)
2019-06-05 15:46:54

*Thread Reply:* what I need is if OS = 9.0 then AE enrollment only else legacy enrollment

Dimi (1547@live.co.uk)
2019-06-05 16:41:10

*Thread Reply:* The only way to have device provisioned as AE is to follow one of the supported AE enrolment methods. NFC bump, afw# token, QR code, or zero-touch (never done this one though). DPC (EMM Client) must take ownership of the device before OS fully boots up. If users skips this step a device will end up in a DA mode. The only way to convert it to AE is to factory reset it and enrol using one of the methods described above. Since AE enrolment starts before device touches EMM you can’t enforce it with a policy (unless it is zero-touch provisioned, but don’t take my work for it). I suggest user education and a solid enrolment manual that comes with every device. https://bayton.org/docs/enterprise-mobility/android/android-enterprise-provisioning-guides/

Jason Bayton
Android Enterprise provisioning guides
What is Android Enterprise?  For information regarding Android Enterprise, including what it is, the deployment scenarios stated below and how it can benefit organisations, have a read of What is Android Enterprise and why is it used? The following guides have been created for reference purposes only. As individual environments differ, some aspects …
Original URL: https://bayton.org/docs/enterprise-mobility/android/android-enterprise-provisioning-guides/

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2019-06-08 19:33:45

*Thread Reply:* It's a tricky one as VMware's criteria options suck for creating advanced groups on which to experiment.

I'd probably approach this external to EMM, spending time getting devices into KME manually first.

Then plan to undergo grouped wipes to have users forced into the KME flow and take it from there.

It'd need communication, a lot of documentation for prepping backups and all that jazz, but when you do go chasing the stragglers there'll be fewer of them.

My normal approach to DA > AE is to push DA onto WP. You do lose access to management capabilities in the short term but it's far less work and comes with stronger security than DA. As folks come in or devices are replaced they can go to FM. But that's just me.

Jeff Mosher (jmosher@ca.ibm.com)
2019-06-08 19:38:24

*Thread Reply:* As always, @Jason Bayton with the great info! I think that's similar to the approach we will need to take to ensure FM of all devices in the future.. The downside is that (painful) period of time where you have legacy DA + WP + FM devices in your environment. Its mainly an issue for our Helpdesks but with proper education and documentation the risks can be mitigated.

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2019-06-08 19:57:34

*Thread Reply:* It's a state many orgs will be in for the next couple of years. DA can disappear as quickly as you can prepare and migrate.

WP and FM are easily distinguished by their Enterprise Version and in a lot of cases the same profile can apply to both deployment scenarios so only basic troubleshooting differs.

If you ever expand to BYOD (because why not, you've got the platform for it!) Your techs will need to understand both sides of AE anyway.

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2019-06-08 19:57:51

End-user devices must be able to reach certain endpoints for access to apps and services. The Network Requirements for Android is a list of known endpoints for current and past versions of enterprise management APIs.

*Thread Reply:* Android connectivity check starting with N MR1 requires https://www.google.com/generate_204 to be reachable, or for the given WiFi network to point to a reachable PAC file

GAL Contacts from Exchange / O365 for android phone Resolution (within car Entertainment also) ?

play.google.com
GALConnect - Apps on Google Play
GALConnect offers unique convenience functions for handling the global address list (GAL) of an Exchange / O365 server. THE GLOBAL ADDRESS LIST (GAL): ALWAYS WITH YOU OFFLINE Thanks to the deep integration with Android, your contacts are directly available in Android. Caller identification is thus technically possible for your entire company, whether on a SmartPhone or in the car. GALConnect is the only solution that allows you to make your global address list available offline (prerequisite: Exchange &gt;=2013 or Office 365). Your employees will now know who is calling you from the company every time they make a call. This increases the productivity of your employees while at the same time minimizing the effort for your administrators. GALConnect was specially developed with the goal of high performance even with large amounts of data. So even 50,000 contacts and more are no problem. The updating of the data also takes place unnoticed in the background, even with larger quantities. GALConnect ALLOWS YOU TO USE IT IN DIFFERENT MODES In "SECURE" mode, contacts remain secure in GALConnect and are NOT transmitted to the system or third-party apps. Incoming calls are identified by an overlay if the phone number is in GALConnect. In the "INFO" mode contacts are constantly synchronized and integrated into your Android system. These contacts are also available to third-party apps. The rules of the work profiles (formerly Android for Work) apply. SECURITY A work profile allows organizations to manage critical business data and apps while leaving everything else on the device to the user. Roll out the GALConnect in such a work profile. Work profiles are managed by administrators and are independent of private accounts, apps and data. Notifications and work profile apps are identified by a work logo by default, making them easy to distinguish from private apps. With work profiles, IT departments can securely manage a work environment without restricting the private use of apps and data by users on their own devices. Your IT Decides how and whether the GAL data available in this way can be used by privately installed apps or not (protected). PRODUCTIVITY - ALWAYS AND EVERYWHERE Download your (offline) GAL version from anywhere in the world. The deep integration as account synchronization allows you to recognize contacts on incoming calls through the standard system. This also allows for number recognition in the car. In addition, the app provides quick access to the GAL contact memory with detailed information. The GAL is downloaded in the background. This means that you have virtually no time-consuming user interaction. MADE IN GERMANY GALConnect was completely designed and developed in Germany. Do you have any questions or suggestions? Write to us: <a href="mailto:support@mobilebox-consulting.de">support@mobilebox-consulting.de</a>

} Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/)
List of desserts
A dessert is typically the sweet course that concludes a meal in the culture of many countries, particularly Western culture. The course usually consists of sweet foods, but may include other items. The word "dessert" originated from the French word desservir "to clear the table" and the negative of the Latin word servire.There are a wide variety of desserts in western cultures, including cakes, cookies, biscuits, gelatins, pastries, ice creams, pies, puddings, and candies. Fruit is also commonly found in dessert courses because of its natural sweetness. Many different cultures have their own variations of similar desserts around the world, such as in Russia, where many breakfast foods such as blini, oladyi, and syrniki can be served with honey and jam to make them popular as desserts.
Original URL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_desserts
} Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/)
Queen of Puddings
Queen of Puddings is a traditional British dessert, consisting of a baked, breadcrumb-thickened mixture, spread with jam and topped with meringue. Similar recipes are called Monmouth Pudding and Manchester Pudding.
Original URL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_of_Puddings

Phil Burk (philburk@mac.com)
2019-08-27 15:33:33

Stupid question time. We have a customer that is seeking to manage a class of android devices (warehouse mgmt devices) via MDM but need to distribute a file to these devices for a specific piece of software. The filetype of this file is not supported for distribution from the MDM (Mobile Iron). There is a custom MDM to support this file and software but the customer really isn't interested in implementing yet another MDM solution for just these devices. I'm familiar with using custom packages on other platforms (macOS, mainly) to drop files in specific locations on the target filesystem. Is this possible to do on Android? Could I create a custom installation package that would drop this file in the proper spot on the target device?

Matthew Shaver (mshaver@us.ibm.com)
2019-08-27 15:37:28

*Thread Reply:* I can’t speak to MI specifically, but I do know that many EMM/UEM solutions support writing files to different locations on Android devices, so this could theoretically be done with a custom package too.

Johannes Harbs (harbs.johannes@gmail.com)
2019-08-27 15:37:36

*Thread Reply:* you could develop an app with the sole purpose of transferring the file to the device. Other EMMs (WS1, SOTI, ...) can push any file to the filesystem, I am not aware of such a functionality in MI.

Phil Burk (philburk@mac.com)
2019-08-27 15:42:54

*Thread Reply:* Client's looking to support a zero-touch workflow for these devices and this file is literally the last thing potentially blocking that. Is this something I should be able to (easily) figure out in Android Studio?

AJ (ajorgensen@mobileiron.com)
2019-08-28 02:41:02

*Thread Reply:* you can use help@work to push a file to an individual device

AJ (ajorgensen@mobileiron.com)
2019-08-28 02:41:25

*Thread Reply:* for fleet wide deployments usually you can do this via xml, for example with Zebra

Matt Dermody (jmdermody@gmail.com)
2019-09-04 18:58:09

*Thread Reply:* Late to the party here, but if they are Zebra devices you can use an MX XML configuration to instruct the devices to retrieve the file from an external file share like an FTP server. My strong recommendation would be to use SOTI or WS1 for rugged/warehouse Android however.

image.png
Andrew Montague (amontague@vmware.com)
2019-09-03 11:47:32

*Thread Reply:* You can still use the DPC identifier on version 6 however.

As per the article:

https://developers.google.com/android/management/provision-device#dpc_identifier_method

"DPC identifier method If Android Device Policy can't be added via QR code or NFC a user or IT admin can follow these steps to provision a fully managed or dedicated device:

Follow the setup wizard on a new or factory-reset device. Enter Wi-Fi login details to connect the device to the internet. When prompted to sign in, enter afw#setup, which downloads Android Device Policy. Scan a QR code or manually enter an enrollment token to provision the device."

Google Developers
Enroll and provision a device  |  Android Management API  |  Google Developers
Original URL: https://developers.google.com/android/management/provision-device#dpc_identifier_method

VMware AirWatch is making some changes that may affect your device enrollments. 

Firstly, if you are using the VMware AirWatch agent in legacy Device Admin (DA) mode, please see this knowledge base (KB) article: https://kb.vmware.com/s/article/79579?lang=en_US. To summarize, if you are using an ELM APK as part of your DA profile, you will need to remove this APK before you can assign any new devices to that profile. Enrollment will fail if this change is not made.

Secondly, there will be redirects implemented for certain Workspace ONE agent URLs. There should be no impact on device enrollment with this change. Further details are contained in the above.

Both of the above changes are scheduled to take place on August 9, 2020.

Thirdly, in case you missed it, please be aware of VMware’s positioning on legacy Device Admin based enrollments. More details can be found in this KB article: https://kb.vmware.com/s/article/79206?lang=en_US

Finally, the VMware AirWatch name shown in the KME portal for Device Owner profile creation will change from “Airwatch” to “Workspace ONE UEM”. We are targeted July 29, 2020 for this change.

If you have any questions, please contact Samsung Knox Support (support.samsungknox.com)

brandobot (brwong@linkedin.com)
2020-12-14 21:08:56

Is there a site where I can find currently supported Android versions? I’m trying to determine what is considered end of life.

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2020-12-14 21:23:35

*Thread Reply:* It's a bit of a piece of string. Depending on the OEM support for the OS on that device can end after 18 or so months (1 year mandatory updates, one year critical only). AER devices have up to Android 10 extended this to 2-3 years (2 years mandatory security updates, 1 critical).

Officially Google stops backporting security updates after about 3 years, but OEMs can continue backporting themselves.

Google rarely make an announcement about proper OS EOL. They did for KitKat as I recall, but I haven't seen much since, devices simply tend to lifecycle out of use over time even when updates and security aren't considered.

brandobot (brwong@linkedin.com)
2020-12-14 22:26:38

*Thread Reply:* thanks for that info @Jason Bayton. We have some devices on older flavors of Android such as 8 and 9, and I’m trying to figure out where to draw the line on what we allow in our MDM.

Andrew Montague (amontague78@gmail.com)
2020-12-15 09:53:28

*Thread Reply:* There are two approaches. One is function based where devices you allow are based on if they support a particular function or not, the second is security based and this is based on your tolerance for potential security flaws.

Both of these approaches will depend on your industry and what the devices are used for. I know of plenty of devices running Android 8 in the wild because they are in warehouses on rugged devices where the risk is considered low and reliability is a must, so pushing the latest OS to them is considered a risky behaviour that could bring down ops if not handled carefully. I also know of business involved in finance who only allow devices with an N-1 policy for point releases not major OS versions because being as up-to-date as possible on security exploits is their absolute priority.

So as you can see it does mean that it's as much a policy as technology decision. As Jason says it's much harder to track than iOS because updates are often left to the manufacture's discretion rather than just Google forcing new versions out. OnePlus have a reputation for implementing new patches quite fast, Samsung are notoriously slow and both approaches have valid arguments for them.

I appreciate this isn't a definitive argument for what you should have in your environment but hopefully it gives you something to think about when deciding.

👍 Jason Bayton, brandobot

https://blog.google/products/android-enterprise/android-12-developer-preview/?utmsource=feedburner&utmmedium=feed&utmcampaign=Feed%3A+blogspot%2FMKuf+%28The+Keyword+%7C+Official+Google+Blog%29|https://blog.google/products/android-enterprise/android-12-developer-preview/?utm[…]d%3A+blogspot%2FMKuf+%28The+Keyword+%7C+Official+Google+Blog%29

Google
Android 12 simplifies security for work devices
With every major Android release, we want to strike the right balance between improving security and manageability and making the platform more usable and private for employees. With Android 12, now in developer preview, we’re introducing a number of features that not only bolster security, but also provide more simplicity and utility for IT and more privacy and productivity for employees. Simplifying password complexityFor users on work profile devices, we’re introducing a more straightforward, modern approach to password restrictions. Instead of granular requirements that often result in easily forgotten passwords, we’re establishing pre-set complexity levels of high, medium or low that will be used to access the device. With Android hardware-backed brute force protections in place since 2016, IT doesn’t have to employ super-complex restrictions, which can still be guessed by computers. By utilizing the new complexity levels along with other Android security protections, including SafetyNet Attestation API and Google Play Protect, IT teams can be assured devices are safe and easy to use for employees.Easily set up a work security challengeAdmins can still utilize a more granular password, if they prefer, through the work security challenge to manage access to business apps in the work profile. The work security challenge enables an IT-approved password for access to data in the work profile, separate from a simplified password for the device. We’ve improved the device setup process to prompt employees if their provided password doesn’t meet complexity requirements set by their admin. Users who receive a prompt can simply choose to increase the strength of their device password or set up a work security challenge to access apps in the work profile. If approved by IT, employees can also switch back to one password for both work and personal if they change their mind. For company-owned devices, admins will be able to choose whether they use the new password complexity levels or continue using the more granular restrictions.Certificate management on unmanaged devicesCertificate management is a critical tool that allows enterprises to enable authentication for employee access to remote services. Today, the process can be seamlessly handled on managed devices through an Enterprise Mobility Management’s (EMM) device policy client, which can programmatically generate keys, install certificates from the Android KeyChain service and present them for authentication. In Android 12, we’re streamlining credential management for unmanaged devices by making the process available to apps beside the device policy client. With this expanded credential management, more companies can extend secure access to employees regardless of their location, a key requirement in the COVID-19 era. Additionally, employees can avoid the cumbersome, manual process of installing certificates themselves.Enrollment-specific IDs for personal devicesFor employee-owned managed devices, we’re creating a new enterprise-specific device identifier that may help enhance privacy in the event an employee leaves their current employer. Instead of relying on hardware identifiers such as IMEI or serial numbers, personal devices will get a new identifier derived programmatically during enrollment. Enrollment-specific IDs allow IT admins to identify the device if it’s re-enrolled at the same organization, even if the device is factory reset. But these IDs limit IT’s ability to track the device if the employee leaves the company. Today’s initial preview covers some of the features you’ll see in the next release of Android with more to come as we get close to launch. Learn about the enterprise features in the Android 12 Developer Preview at the Android developers website. To give Android 12 a try, you can download it to a Pixel device today.
Original URL: https://blog.google/products/android-enterprise/android-12-developer-preview/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+blogspot%2FMKuf+%28The+Keyword+%7C+Official+Google+Blog%29
👍 Ray Domingue

2021-03-05 23:21:59

Is anyone aware of a way to suppress OTA/OS updates (indefinitely) on Android Enterprise OS 9+ (kiosk mode)?

Raul (rnadal@mobileiron.com)
2021-03-07 04:52:26

*Thread Reply:* If you use Samsung, that’s an option available on Knox Service Plugin OEMConfig app. Free when applied to Device Owner Mode devices.

If that’s not an option because the OEM you use don’t provide OEMConfig app, you can identify the system app that handles OTA upgrades and disable it. I did it in the past and turns the check updates button useless.

If you enable it again later, it recovers and user can upgrade again.

Question for the Zebra experts out there, we are going to start deploying MC93's that originally shipped with Android 8.1 but I see Android 10 is available. What is the best approach to updating these? Also what is the difference between the Full Image vs Life Guard updates? I'm assuming LG updates are like month security patches and that I will need to first push out the full image but would love some guidance as I've never worked with these devices before. Also is there any reason why I wouldn't want to update from Android 8.1 to Android 10 on these things?

ninex (me@willworland.com)
2021-04-15 02:03:13

*Thread Reply:* It would appear that they do support 10. They have upgrade instructions here: https://www.zebra.com/us/en/support-downloads/software/operating-system/mc9300-operating-system.html Looks like there isn't an Android 9 BSP, so you would likely go from 8.1 to 10. If you have physical access to the devices, it's as easy as setting up an SD card w/ the right files and rebooting in recovery. If you wish to update via EMM, it depends on the EMM, how much bandwidth you have and on what sort of connection. If cellular, you may want to validate you have enough available data on plan before updating.

Zebra Technologies
MC9300 Operating System Support &amp; Downloads | Zebra
Find information on drivers, software, support, downloads and more for your Zebra MC9300 Operating System.
Original URL: https://www.zebra.com/us/en/support-downloads/software/operating-system/mc9300-operating-system.html
Boe (bkelley1982@gmail.com)
2021-04-15 02:11:21

*Thread Reply:* @ninex thanks but what I'm trying to understand is the difference between the full file vs the Life Guard update

ninex (me@willworland.com)
2021-04-15 02:20:47

*Thread Reply:* Oh, yeah, so the Full Image typically has the initial primary OS and whatever patches were available at the time of release. The LG's are supplemental updates for firmware patches and security updates. Any LG's you don't have on your Oreo devices will already be wrapped up in the v10 full image.

ninex (me@willworland.com)
2021-04-15 02:21:33

*Thread Reply:* after you get to the v10 full image, you will have some LG's to push.

Matt Dermody (jmdermody@gmail.com)

Matt Dermody (jmdermody@gmail.com)

ZL (mobilepros@zolik.co.uk)
2021-10-28 19:43:41

*Thread Reply:* If I remember correctly, there is no retire button for the device, only for apps, but in all cases device will be wiped. Enterprise wipe, device wipe.

Woody (eric.woodland@trust.tc)
2021-10-28 20:14:51

*Thread Reply:* @ZL trying to assist a customer who’s migrating from WS1. The API indicates that a retire was initiated, but the device wiped. My guess is that it was an AE Dedicated Device and Retire was initiated (which wiped it).

DirkC (dcarey@vmware.com)
2021-10-29 16:02:46

*Thread Reply:* "Retire" isn't really a command inside Workspace ONE UEM. There is Delete device (enterprise wipes DA and Device Wipes DO), Enterprise wipe remove corp profiles and will throw prompts up to uninstall apps (user can cancel). Device Wipe does a factory restore.

👍 Woody
Woody (eric.woodland@trust.tc)

*Thread Reply:* As a former WIFI engineer I would still verify that it is not WIFI related. Matt Dermody (jmdermody@gmail.com)
2022-11-07 13:29:19

*Thread Reply:* Are you connecting via HTTPS? It’s possible the SSL cert chain isn’t trusted by Android. This is especially common if there is an intermediate cert in use. You can try to connect to the designated host URL via Chrome on the device and see if you see any SSL issues. You can use your EMM to install the intermediate cert on the device so that it can trust the connection.

Matt Dermody (jmdermody@gmail.com)
2022-11-07 13:30:36

*Thread Reply:* @Jason Bayton Have wiretraced from Android device before but not using the Wireshark app. Zebra has a built in wireless trace logging tool on their devices that can generate .pcaps. They can be retrieved and reviewed using Wireshark though

Caryn (Csnshop@icloud.com)
2023-04-19 20:49:26

Has anyone managed proprietary apps on non-GMS Androids in China? Wondering what quarterly updates / app management is going to look like for devices distributed in many different physical locations. We can sideload the initial app, but cannot sideload updates.

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2023-04-20 12:46:39

*Thread Reply:* Depends on the MDM you’re using, because you absolutely can push apps and updates via the MDM directly with DO/DA on AOSP hardware, as long as it’s supported by your vendor.

For OTAs, AOSP leans on the same update engine as certified devices, but not necessarily the same infrastructure. Many GMS OEMs use GOTA, but third parties or OEM-specific FOTA servers (aka E-FOTA for Samsung) exist. As for frequency, that’s between you and the OEM/ODM you’ve bestowed your business with. There’s no contractual obligation but if you’re paying them you’ll have leverage.

👍 Caryn
Caryn (Csnshop@icloud.com)
2023-04-20 15:54:12

*Thread Reply:* Doesn't the .apk have to be hosted in China?

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2023-04-20 17:27:53

*Thread Reply:* Nope, as long as there's connectivity between the EMM and devices, it'll be pushed from the EMM.

Caryn (Csnshop@icloud.com)
2023-04-21 14:17:31

*Thread Reply:* What about the great firewall? How is communication between that and the MDM/app outside of China? Doesn't it require a presence in China?

Jason Bayton (jason@bayton.org)
2023-04-21 14:29:30

*Thread Reply:* The great firewall doesn't block everything, so as long as the vendor confirms they have no connectivity issues into CN then you'll be fine. As it's non-GMS the EMM will lean on their own notification and comm protocols and not those of FCM through Google

👍 RJ
